  <static seed="268" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionApplication/FractionAdditionWordProblems10.pg">
    <statement><p>Ken walked <m>{{\frac{1}{10}}}</m> of a mile in the morning, and then walked <m>{{\frac{1}{5}}}</m> of a mile in the afternoon. How far did Ken walk altogether?</p>
<p>Ken walked a total of <fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/> of a mile.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{3}{10}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This is an addition problem.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   {{\frac{1}{10}}} + {{\frac{1}{5}}} 
      \amp = \frac{1}{10}+\frac{1 \cdot 2}{5 \cdot 2} \\
      \amp = \frac{1}{10} + \frac{2}{10} \\
      \amp = \frac{1+2}{10} \\
      
      \amp = {{\frac{3}{10}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Ken walked a total of <m>{{\frac{3}{10}}}</m> miles altogether.</p>
</solution>
